We have the system of equations

\begin{align*}
x+\frac{1}{y}&=10,\\
y+\frac{1}{x}&=\frac{5}{12}.
\end{align*}

Multiplying the first equation by $y$ and the second equation by $x$, we get

\begin{align*}
xy+1&=10y,\\
xy+\frac{x}{y}&=\frac{5x}{12}.
\end{align*}

Subtracting the second equation from the first, we obtain

\begin{align*}
1-\frac{x}{y}&=10y-\frac{5x}{12},\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{12-x}{y}&=120y-\frac{5x}{12},\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 12-x&=1440y^2-\frac{5xy}{12}.
\end{align*}

Multiplying both sides by 12, we get

\begin{align*}
144-12x&=17280y^2-\frac{5xy}{1}.
\end{align*}

Rearranging, we have

\begin{align*}
12x+5xy&=17280y^2-144.
\end{align*}

Factoring out $x$, we get

\begin{align*}
x(12+5y)&=17280y^2-144.
\end{align*}

Since $x$ is nonzero, we can divide both sides by $x$ to get

\begin{align*}
12+5y&=\frac{17280y^2-144}{x}.
\end{align*}

Substituting $y=10-x$ from the first equation, we have

\begin{align*}
12+5(10-x)&=\frac{17280(10-x)^2-144}{x},\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 62-5x&=\frac{17280(100-20x+x^2)-144}{x},\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 62-5x&=\frac{1728000-34560x+17280x^2-144}{x},\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 62-5x&=17280x-34560,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 17342&=17285x,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{17342}{17285}=\boxed{\frac{618}{653}}.
\end{align*}

