\begin{align*}
\frac{\sin t}{\sqrt{2}p\cos t - 1} &= \frac{\sin(t + \theta) - \sin t}{\sqrt{2}p\cos(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\cos t} \\
\Rightarrow \sin t(\sqrt{2}p\cos(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\cos t) &= (\sqrt{2}p\cos t - 1)(\sin(t + \theta) - \sin t).
\end{align*}

Expanding and simplifying, we get
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{2}p\sin t\cos(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\sin t\cos t &= \sqrt{2}p\cos t\sin(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\cos t\sin t - \sqrt{2}p\cos t\sin t + \sin t \\
\Rightarrow \sqrt{2}p\sin t\cos(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\sin t\cos t &= \sqrt{2}p\cos t\sin(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\cos t\sin t + \sin t.
\end{align*}

Dividing both sides by $\sin t$ (since $t$ is not zero), we get
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{2}p\cos(t + \theta) - \sqrt{2}\cos t &= \sqrt{2}p\cos t\tan(t + \theta) - \cos t + 1.
\end{align*}

Since this equation must hold for all $t$, we can equate the coefficients of $\cos t$ and $\cos(t + \theta)$ on both sides.

