 Solution:
We can rewrite the expression using the properties of logarithms:

\begin{align*}
\frac{2}{\log_4{2000^6}} + \frac{3}{\log_5{2000^6}} &= \frac{2}{\log_4{(2000^6)}} + \frac{3}{\log_5{(2000^6)}} \\
&= \frac{2}{6\log_4{2000}} + \frac{3}{6\log_5{2000}} \\
&= \frac{1}{3\log_4{2000}} + \frac{1}{2\log_5{2000}}.
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the change of base formula to rewrite the logarithms with base 10:

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{3\log_4{2000}} + \frac{1}{2\log_5{2000}} &= \frac{1}{3\frac{\log{2000}}{\log{4}}} + \frac{1}{2\frac{\log{2000}}{\log{5}}}.
\end{align*}

Now, we can simplify the expression:

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{3\frac{\log{2000}}{\log{4}}} + \frac{1}{2\frac{\log{2000}}{\log{5}}} &= \frac{\log{4}}{3\log{2000}} + \frac{\log{5}}{2\log{2000}} \\
&= \frac{\log{4} + \log{5}}{6\log{2000}}.
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the properties of logarithms to combine the numerator:

\begin{align*}
\frac{\log{4} + \log{5}}{6\log{2000}} &= \frac{\log{(4\cdot5)}}{6\log{2000}} \\
&= \frac{\log{20}}{6\log{2000}}.
\end{align*}

Finally, we can simplify the expression further:

\begin{align*}
\frac{\log{20}}{6\log{2000}} &= \frac{\log{20}}{6(\log{200}+\log{10})} \\
&= \frac{\log{20}}{6(\log{20}+\log{10})} \\
&= \frac{\log{20}}{6\log{200}} \\
&= \frac{1}{6\log_2{200}}.
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the change of base formula again to rewrite the logarithm with base 10:

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{6\log_2{200}} &= \frac{1}{6\frac{\log{200}}{\log{2}}} \\
&= \frac{\log{2}}{6\log{200}}.
\end{align*}

Finally, we can simplify the expression:

\begin{align*}
\frac{\log{2}}{6\log{200}} &= \frac{\log{2}}{6(\log{2}+\log{100})} \\
&= \frac{\log{2}}{6\log{200}} \\
&= \frac{1}{6\log_2{200}}.
\end{align*}

So, the final answer is \[\boxed{\frac{1}{6\log_2{200}}}.\]

