Since the circle is tangent to the parabola at $(2,4),$ the radius of the circle is equal to the distance between $(2,4)$ and the center of the circle.

Let the center of the circle be $(h,k).$ Then the distance between $(2,4)$ and $(h,k)$ is equal to the radius of the circle.

Using the distance formula, we have

\begin{align*}
(h-2)^2+(k-4)&=r^2.
\end{align*}

Since the circle passes through $(0,1),$ we also have

\begin{align*}
(h-0)^2+(k-1)&=r^2.
\end{align*}

Subtracting these two equations, we get

\begin{align*}
h^2+k-5&=0.
\end{align*}

Substituting $h^2+k-5=0$ into the first equation, we have

\begin{align*}
(h-2)^2+k-4&=r^2,\\
